In this Sanhita, unless the context otherwise requires,—

(1) 'audio-video electronic means' includes use of any communication device for the purposes of video conferencing, recording of processes of identification, search and seizure or evidence collection or transmission of electronic communication;

(3) 'bailable offence' means an offence which is shown as bailable in the First Schedule, or which is made bailable by any other law for the time being in force;

(7) 'cognizable offence' means an offence for which a police officer may arrest without warrant;

(8) 'complaint' means any allegation made orally or in writing to a Magistrate, with a view to his taking action under this Sanhita, that some person, whether known or unknown, has committed an offence;

(22) 'police report' means a report forwarded by a police officer to a Magistrate under sub-section (1) of section 193.

(1) Every investigation under this Chapter shall be completed without unnecessary delay, and on completion of investigation, the officer in charge of the police station shall forward to a Magistrate empowered to take cognizance of the offence on a police report.

(2) The report shall state—
(a) the names of the parties;
(b) the nature of the information;
(c) the names of persons who appear to be acquainted with the circumstances;
(d) whether any offence appears to have been committed and, if so, by whom;
(e) whether the accused has been arrested;
(f) whether he has been released on bond.

**Timeline:** The charge sheet shall be filed within 60 days for offences punishable with imprisonment up to 10 years, and 90 days for offences punishable with death, life imprisonment or imprisonment exceeding 10 years.

**Note:** Corresponds to CrPC Section 173.

(1) Subject to the provisions of this Chapter, any Magistrate of the first class, and any Magistrate of the second class specially empowered in this behalf, may take cognizance of any offence—
(a) upon receiving a complaint of facts which constitute such offence;
(b) upon a police report of such facts;
(c) upon information received from any person other than a police officer, or upon his own knowledge, that such offence has been committed.

(2) A Magistrate taking cognizance of an offence on a complaint shall examine upon oath the complainant and the witnesses present.

**Note:** Corresponds to CrPC Section 190.
